---
import BenchmarkInteractions from '../components/BenchmarkInteractions.astro';
import BenchmarkDashboard from '../components/home/BenchmarkDashboard.astro';
import { loadBenchmarkMetrics } from '../data/benchmarkData';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const benchmarkMetrics = await loadBenchmarkMetrics();
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Benchmarks"
  description="Explore generated-code benchmark snapshots for Ultraviolet: build pass rates, test results, token usage, cost, and turns across AI models and tasks."
>
  <article class="article-page status-page benchmarks-page">
    <header>
      <p class="eyebrow">Generated-code benchmarks</p>
      <h1>Benchmarks</h1>
      <p>
        The uv-benchmarks harness measures how AI models perform when writing
        Ultraviolet on fixed tasks: whether the result builds, passes tests and
        scanner checks, stays organized, and what it costs in tokens, dollars,
        and turns.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="status-page-section" aria-label="Benchmark explorer">
      <BenchmarkDashboard metrics={benchmarkMetrics} />
    </section>

    <section id="methodology" class="status-page-section">
      <h2>Methodology and reproducibility</h2>
      <p>
        Each run gives a model a fixed task specification and records the
        outcome of the generated Ultraviolet project. Scores weight project
        organization, build and functional checks, code quality, performance,
        and bug or security findings; token, cost, and turn counts come from
        the model provider's usage reporting for the run.
      </p>
      <p>
        These results are snapshots, not independently reproducible claims
        yet. The harness repository is being prepared for public release;
        until it is published, treat the numbers above as indicative. The
        status pill on the explorer shows whether you are viewing live harness
        output or the bundled snapshot.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you want to evaluate generated Ultraviolet yourself today, the
        <a href="/docs/ai-written-code-review/">AI-written code review model</a>
        describes what reviewers should check, and the
        <a href="/docs/specification/">specification</a> defines the exact
        rules the output must satisfy.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
  <BenchmarkInteractions />
</BaseLayout>
